english:
  title: A Record of the House of Ko, Star Master of Tamna
  author: Jung Yi-o
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the land of Tamna there were no people at first. Upon that mountainous realm of extraordinary beauty stands Mount Halla, serene above the misty sea. The divine spirit and harmonious breath descended, manifesting three divine beings in the northern cavern called Moheung. They emerged together as one: Ko Ulna, Yang Ulna, and Bu Ulna. Ko Ulna became the founder of the Ko clan. All three lived by fishing and hunting.

    According to the genealogy, the king of Japan fathered seven daughters and sent four to the land of the Red Nomads. He commanded three of his daughters thus: "In the southwestern sea lies a mountain that has given birth to three divine brothers who will establish a kingdom, yet lack companions. Go and serve them. Your descendants shall multiply and prosper greatly." He placed them in a wooden vessel, furnished with seeds of five grains and cattle, and sent divine guardians with them. When they reached the eastern shore of Tamna, the three divine brothers, out hunting, encountered them. The guardian spirits—robed in crimson silk and wearing scarlet sashes—ascended into the heavens and vanished. The three brothers each took a bride from among the maidens and settled near Moheung Cavern. Within years their household flourished and prospered.

    Generations passed until the fifteenth descendant of Ko Ulna—Ko Hu and his younger brother Ko Ch'ing—prepared to present themselves at the court of Silla. A guest star appeared in the heavens. The royal astronomers reported: "This portends the arrival of divine beings from distant lands." Soon after, the Ko brothers crossed the sea and landed at Tamjin, then proceeded to Silla. The king received them with great joy. Because of the portentous star, he granted Ko Hu the title Star Master and honored Ko Ch'ing as a prince, conferring upon them the territory of Tamna—named for the sea-crossing from Tamjin to Silla.

    When the founding king unified the three kingdoms, the Star Master was Ko Cha-gyŏn and the prince was Yang Ch'a-mi, descendant of Yang Ulna. The title was changed to Yang because the sound resembled their original name. They were to present themselves at court once per generation. The founding king showed them extraordinary favor, receiving them three times daily with imperial hospitality and lavish gifts extending even to their servants and oarsmen. Yet for generations they merely inherited their hereditary titles without rising to prominence in the kingdom—until Ko Yu first passed the examination for tribute-bearing officials.

    In the year of Chŏng Wang, Ko Yu placed first in the provincial examination and two years later ranked third on the examination list under Li Chak-chŏng, eventually becoming Right Minister. His son Cho Ki, originally named T'ang Yŏ, passed the examination under Han Chik-yu in the year of Ye Wang and later served in the royal bureaus, distinguished for his fearless counsel. He was appointed to oversee the examination of the year of Ui Wang, eventually rising to the rank of Prime Minister and Minister of Personnel. His poems, collected in two volumes, circulated widely.

    The great-grandson of this Prime Minister, Ko Chŏk, received his degree during the reign of Wŏn Wang and entered the imperial bureaucracy. When the Three Battalions of Divine Righteousness rebelled and invaded Tamna in 1273, Ko Chŏk was appointed Chief Administrator to pacify and resettle the remaining population. When the rebellion was finally suppressed four years later, he traveled to court where the king personally conferred upon him a golden tablet and sealed his authority. In later years his title was changed to Commander of Military and Civilian Affairs.

    Thus did his line rise to prominence. His fifth-generation descendant, In T'an, inherited the rank. When Yüan sought to launch an invasion of Japan, ordering the preparation of nine hundred warships and all necessary supplies, Yüan commanded Tamna to construct one hundred vessels. All the planning fell to In T'an. When Yüan later appointed him General of Manifest Might and Administrator, In T'an worked with Vice-Administrator Mun Ch'ang-u and Counselor Kim Sŏn to petition Yüan to return Tamna to Koryŏ's sovereignty. King Ch'ungnyŏl was moved by his loyalty and appointed him Star Master Cloud-Plume General of the Upper Ranks, bestowing upon him crimson sashes, purple robes, and the ceremonial canopy—honors that had originated in Silla's time.

    The king declared: "From Silla's age unto this day, your family's unwavering devotion to the realm merits praise. Let the office of Star Master never fall from your line through all generations to come."

    In T'an's line continued to flourish. His descendant Ko Sin-gyŏl served as Vice Commander of the Western Provinces under Hong Wu. When the Yüan emperor led campaigns against the Jurchen, Sin-gyŏl remained in his post. When rebels attempted insurrection, killing a provincial commander, Sin-gyŏl conspired with the royal prince to suppress them. Though the rebels surrounded both houses for three days, slaughtering their livestock, Sin-gyŏl and the prince escaped. With the state's authority they crushed the rebellion. Later, when Japanese corsairs—six hundred vessels—attacked Tamna's shores, Sin-gyŏl, though struck by arrows, held firm in his defense and received promotion and reward. He was further honored with the title of Star Master, receiving crimson sashes, purple robes, the ceremonial canopy, and gifts of bows and arrows.

    Sin-gyŏl fathered four sons: Pong In, Pong Ŭi, Pong Ye, and Pong Chi. The first two died young. Pong Ye, styled Paek-gong, and Pong Chi, styled Jung-myŏng, served the founding king. Pong Ye rose to General-in-Chief, while Pong Chi became a Stalwart General. Pong Ye, as the eldest, inherited the Star Master title; Pong Chi preceded him in death.

    Pong Chi's son Tŭk-jong, now Keeper of the Palace Kitchens, maintained his father's grave with utmost reverence, earning the profound respect of all the region's people. The throne itself took note, marking his filial piety with honor. In the current year, Tŭk-jong became Vice Director of the Righteous Surplus Storehouse. He submitted a comprehensive petition to the throne addressing Tamna's affairs, eliminating long-standing abuses. That autumn, when the king held civil examinations, Tŭk-jong's policy response ranked thirteenth in the second class. The following year he inherited the Star Master rank and rose successively through the posts of Censor, Officer of the Board of Punishments, and Counselor of the Board of Rites. This autumn, having completed an embassy to his homeland, he earned the esteem of all scholars.

    Tŭk-jong spoke to me thus: "Our house took root in the cavern of Moheung. From Silla's age to this present day, we have inherited the Star Master rank through endless generations, serving the kingdom with unceasing loyalty. Yet time passes swiftly and the old deeds fade. I fear that without written record, all will be lost to posterity. The genealogy is incomplete, so I beg you to preserve at least the outline."

    When I heard this, I recalled that Yi In was born of the Hollow Mulberry and Fushuo descended upon Fuyan—these seemed strange and doubtful to me. But upon reading the commentary to the ode on the birth of the people, the ancient scholars wrote: "In heaven and earth's beginning, there were no people. Yet people arose through transformation—the vital breath of heaven and earth brought them forth." Observing thus the deeds of Tŭk-jong's ancestors, I came to understand that divine beings are born otherwise than common mortals. How fitting then that their forms are robust, their achievements luminous, their line unbroken through the ages. And Tŭk-jong, though not yet thirty, grows ever more humble and radiant, his noble character bearing the very essence of those great ministers of old.

    Ah! The fortune of the Ko house shall not end!
